{
  "text": "Levinson and Lurie suggest that feminization will bring changes in four dimensions of the medical profession: in the patient-physician relationship, in the local delivery of care, in the global delivery of care to the society as a whole and in the medical profession itself [CITATION_1] . Empirical evidence from high-income countries shows that female physicians work fewer hours, particularly at a younger age, see less patients than their male peers [CITATION_2] , are less inclined to work in rural areas [CITATION_3] and concentrate disproportionally in \"soft\" specialties [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . This has triggered concerns on the potential consequences for the availability and accessibility of medical services to the population [CITATION_6] . Evidence also exists of positive aspects of female physicians' different practice patterns, such as spending more time with their patients [CITATION_7] , writing fewer prescriptions and referring cases more often [CITATION_8] .",
